## When to use
When you need to inspect and analyze the packets flowing through your network interface for troubleshooting or monitoring purposes.

## Approach
Use the `shell_exec` tool with the `tcpdump` command. Common options include `-i eth0` to specify the network interface, `-n` to avoid DNS resolution, and `-v` for verbose output. To capture traffic in real-time, you can run tcpdump continuously or use filters like `tcp` to focus on TCP traffic.

## Example
```sh
shell_exec "tcpdump -i eth0 -n -vv"
```
This example uses the `shell_exec` tool to run an `tcpdump` command that captures all network traffic in real-time from the Ethernet interface (eth0), providing detailed information about each packet without DNS resolution.

## Pitfalls
- Ensure that the system has installed and configured the `tcpdump` utility.
- Be aware of the performance impact as tcpdump can be resource-intensive, especially when capturing large volumes of data.